But in school, there was no
opera class, so will you tell us

00:16:26.150 --> 00:16:30.170
about your chorus class and
your participation there?

00:16:30.170 --> 00:16:37.000 position:56%
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: Yes, in that
class, all the children were divided

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:42.930
into two groups, and one
group was called the Robins,

00:16:42.930 --> 00:16:45.440
and the Robins could sing.

00:16:45.440 --> 00:16:48.660
And the other group was
called the Sparrows,

00:16:48.660 --> 00:16:55.100
and Sparrows were told never to
sing out, only to mouth the words.

00:16:56.940 --> 00:17:00.270
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: Did
you follow that rule?

00:17:00.270 --> 00:17:03.030
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG:
In the chorus class?

00:17:03.030 --> 00:17:05.620
I had no choice but to do it.

00:17:05.620 --> 00:17:08.980
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: Did you ever sing
just for pleasure, for yourself,

00:17:08.980 --> 00:17:12.180
after you were told you
were just a sparrow?

00:17:12.180 --> 00:17:13.480
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: Oh, yeah.

00:17:13.480 --> 00:17:18.050
In the shower and in my dreams.

00:17:18.050 --> 00:17:25.390
But I should say that
I did play the piano,

00:17:25.390 --> 00:17:31.220
and then I also played the cello,
which is a very nice instrument,

00:17:31.220 --> 00:17:33.960
so I could be in the
school orchestra.

00:17:33.960 --> 00:17:38.080
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: And when you were a
little older, maybe in junior high

00:17:38.080 --> 00:17:42.110
or high school, what other
activities did you participate in?

00:17:42.110 --> 00:17:44.170
So, you were in the
school orchestra;

00:17:44.170 --> 00:17:46.900
did you have any after
school activities?

00:17:46.900 --> 00:17:51.520
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: Yes, I
was what we called "a twirler."

00:17:51.520 --> 00:17:53.900
Do you know what a baton is?

00:17:53.900 --> 00:17:56.860
Have you seen them
at sporting events?

00:17:56.860 --> 00:17:59.910
So, I went to every football game,

00:17:59.910 --> 00:18:03.990
and at halftime we
twirled the batons.

00:18:03.990 --> 00:18:05.290
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: You twirled.

00:18:05.290 --> 00:18:06.640
Were you good at it?

00:18:06.640 --> 00:18:07.940
Were you a good twirler?

00:18:07.940 --> 00:18:09.240
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: Yeah.

00:18:09.240 --> 00:18:11.540
I was pretty good at it.

00:18:12.610 --> 00:18:17.190
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: Justice Ginsburg,
when you went on to college

00:18:17.190 --> 00:18:19.860
in the 1950s, many people assumed

00:18:19.860 --> 00:18:23.520
that girls were there
only to find husbands.

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:27.210
What was that like knowing that
that's what a lot of people

00:18:27.210 --> 00:18:31.270
around you thought when
they saw you in college?

00:18:32.470 --> 00:18:34.570
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: I went
to a school in New York state.

00:18:34.570 --> 00:18:39.540
It was called Cornell
University, and in that school,

00:18:39.540 --> 00:18:43.400
there were four boys to every girl.

00:18:43.400 --> 00:18:47.520
So yes, that was a school where
parents would send their girls

00:18:47.520 --> 00:18:52.130
because if you couldn't find
a husband at Cornell, then,

00:18:52.130 --> 00:18:56.500
four-to-one, you were hopeless.

00:18:59.130 --> 00:19:05.990 position:56%
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: You did meet a young
man there named Marty Ginsburg.

00:19:05.990 --> 00:19:11.130
Did he also think you were
in college to find a husband?

00:19:11.130 --> 00:19:19.250
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: Maybe he
was in college to find a wife.

00:19:19.250 --> 00:19:21.420
Anyway, one of the
reasons I loved him

00:19:21.420 --> 00:19:25.880
so much is he cared
that I had a brain.

00:19:27.180 --> 00:19:30.610
And so we were very good friends.

00:19:30.610 --> 00:19:34.570
We talked about everything.

00:19:34.570 --> 00:19:39.460
He would ask me what
classes I was taking

00:19:39.460 --> 00:19:46.670
and then he would sign
up for the same classes.

00:19:46.670 --> 00:19:51.500
Something I didn't know then
but I soon found out ...

00:19:51.500 --> 00:19:56.590
I already told you that
cooking was not my strong point,

00:19:56.590 --> 00:19:58.540
but my husband was a great chef.

00:19:58.540 --> 00:20:03.040
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: So, who did
the cooking in your family?

00:20:03.040 --> 00:20:07.420 position:56%
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: So it
started out, I was the everyday cook

00:20:07.420 --> 00:20:10.870
and my husband was the
weekend and "company" cook.

00:20:10.870 --> 00:20:14.490
I was never allowed
to cook for guests.

00:20:14.490 --> 00:20:19.790
I had one cookbook, it was
called "60 Minute Chef,"

00:20:19.790 --> 00:20:23.930
and that meant nothing
took longer than one hour

00:20:23.930 --> 00:20:28.150
from the time you got home 'til
the dinner was on the table.

00:20:28.150 --> 00:20:32.180
I had seven things that I made,
and when I got up to number seven,

00:20:32.180 --> 00:20:34.860
we went back to number one.

00:20:35.930 --> 00:20:39.550
So my daughter, when she
was about high school age,

00:20:39.550 --> 00:20:42.310
noticed an enormous difference
between her daddy's cooking

00:20:42.310 --> 00:20:44.640
and her mommy's cooking,

00:20:44.640 --> 00:20:48.730
and she decided daddy should
be the cook every day,

00:20:48.730 --> 00:20:52.360
not just on weekends.

00:20:52.360 --> 00:20:55.120
And so it has been now for ...

00:20:55.120 --> 00:20:58.570
well, he died in 2010.

00:20:58.570 --> 00:21:03.210
But my daughter, because she was
responsible for my husband taking

00:21:03.210 --> 00:21:07.430
over the kitchen, now comes
once a month to cook for me.

00:21:07.430 --> 00:21:09.390 position:56%
And she fills the freezer with food,

00:21:09.390 --> 00:21:13.380
and then when the supply
is finished,

00:21:13.380 --> 00:21:15.520
she comes back and cooks some more.

00:21:15.520 --> 00:21:17.800
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: That's a very
nice thing for a daughter to do.

00:21:17.800 --> 00:21:19.100
Is she a good cook, too?

00:21:19.100 --> 00:21:22.050
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: Yeah,
she learned from the master.

00:21:22.050 --> 00:21:26.470
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: I'll add that
Justice Ginsburg's daughter,

00:21:26.470 --> 00:21:30.120
Jane Ginsburg, is also a
professor at Columbia Law School.

00:21:30.120 --> 00:21:35.380
So she cooks, teaches law,
and does a few other things.

00:21:35.380 --> 00:21:40.590
Today, things have changed from
when you were in college more

00:21:40.590 --> 00:21:43.240
and in high school and younger.

00:21:43.240 --> 00:21:48.270 position:56%
More people understand that girls
and boys both go to school to learn,

00:21:48.270 --> 00:21:50.530
to be able to grow up
to do interesting work,

00:21:50.530 --> 00:21:54.120
and to take control of
their own lives as adults

00:21:54.120 --> 00:21:56.210
because they have an education.

00:21:56.210 --> 00:22:00.390
But, Justice Ginsburg, what would
you like the students to learn

00:22:00.390 --> 00:22:05.680
or to understand from your
own less-than-equal experience

00:22:05.680 --> 00:22:08.300
as a girl and young woman?

00:22:09.680 --> 00:22:11.510
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: I
would like the students to know

00:22:11.510 --> 00:22:15.520
that they can be free
to be you and me.

00:22:15.520 --> 00:22:21.270
That is, free to do whatever you
have the talent and are willing

00:22:21.270 --> 00:22:27.400
to work hard enough to do;
that there are no closed doors.

00:22:27.400 --> 00:22:29.370
So, it used to be ...

00:22:29.370 --> 00:22:32.450
you heard Debbie tell
you that there was a time

00:22:32.450 --> 00:22:37.780
when women were not allowed
to be pilots in planes.

00:22:37.780 --> 00:22:40.320
Men were not allowed to be nurses.

00:22:40.320 --> 00:22:48.640
Now, there are no such restrictions
anymore, so a girl can grow

00:22:48.640 --> 00:22:54.360 position:56%
up thinking, "Whatever I like to do,
if I'm willing to work for it enough

00:22:54.360 --> 00:22:59.790
to achieve the learning that
I need to do it, I could do it

00:22:59.790 --> 00:23:07.450
and nobody will say - as they often
said to me - 'We really don't want

00:23:07.450 --> 00:23:12.230
to have any lady lawyers
in this place'."

00:23:12.230 --> 00:23:17.410
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: Well, you became
a lady lawyer and you specialized

00:23:17.410 --> 00:23:24.830
in cases where you were fighting
against unequal treatment of men

00:23:24.830 --> 00:23:26.810
and women, girls and boys.

00:23:26.810 --> 00:23:29.340
And in the cases you
brought, you argued to Judges

00:23:29.340 --> 00:23:33.030 position:56%
that a person's choices shouldn't
be limited just because she happened

00:23:33.030 --> 00:23:36.500
to be born a girl,
happened to be born a boy.

00:23:36.500 --> 00:23:39.930
Can you tell us why you felt,

00:23:39.930 --> 00:23:42.810
and still feel I assume,
so strongly about this?

00:23:42.810 --> 00:23:44.110
Tell us why ...

00:23:44.110 --> 00:23:48.070
And also, if I can make
a two-fer question here,

00:23:48.070 --> 00:23:50.450
tell us why you thought society had

00:23:50.450 --> 00:23:53.930
such rules limiting
what girls could do.

00:23:56.930 --> 00:24:00.310
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: I
thought it was a tremendous waste

00:24:00.310 --> 00:24:03.440
of people's talents.

00:24:03.440 --> 00:24:09.660
Boys and girls have
a range of talents,

00:24:09.660 --> 00:24:13.460
and to say that boys can only do
this and girls can only do that,

00:24:13.460 --> 00:24:16.510
was just wasting the
talent of a lot of girls

00:24:16.510 --> 00:24:18.090
who could do what boys were doing,

00:24:18.090 --> 00:24:22.240
and boys who could do
what girls were doing.

00:24:22.240 --> 00:24:25.740
So I thought everybody
would be better off

00:24:25.740 --> 00:24:32.740
if people could do whatever it is
that they have the talent to do,

00:24:32.740 --> 00:24:38.990
and it shouldn't matter
whether they're a boy or a girl.

00:24:38.990 --> 00:24:42.610
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: Why do you think
those rules, those limitations,

00:24:42.610 --> 00:24:45.850
were put on girls, for example?

00:24:45.850 --> 00:24:51.000
Why did society say, "No, young
Ruth, you shouldn't be a lawyer."

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:54.450
Or to somebody else, "You
shouldn't be an airline pilot

00:24:54.450 --> 00:24:56.550
because you're a woman."

00:24:56.550 --> 00:24:58.250
Why do you think?

00:24:58.250 --> 00:25:03.190
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: Well, some
people said all those "no's" were

00:25:03.190 --> 00:25:06.910
to protect women, so
they couldn't be pilots

00:25:06.910 --> 00:25:10.180
because that was a
dangerous occupation.

00:25:11.870 --> 00:25:14.720
The important thing to understand,

00:25:14.720 --> 00:25:20.830
it turned out women were
not really protected.

00:25:20.830 --> 00:25:27.090
Instead, as one Supreme Court
Justice said, they were in a cage

00:25:27.090 --> 00:25:34.960
and couldn't get out to
do what they wanted to do

00:25:34.960 --> 00:25:41.070
and were ready, willing,
and able to do.

00:25:41.070 --> 00:25:44.890
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: I started out
talking about you as someone

00:25:44.890 --> 00:25:47.670
who has disagreed with
unfairness and with discrimination,

00:25:47.670 --> 00:25:51.260
and with inequality since you
were a girl, so I would say

00:25:51.260 --> 00:25:54.360
that you are an awesome arguer.

00:25:54.360 --> 00:25:56.670 position:56%
I think you're a champion disagreer,

00:25:56.670 --> 00:25:59.910
so now I'd like to get
back to that in this way.

00:25:59.910 --> 00:26:02.670 position:56%
Supreme Court Justice Antonin Scalia

00:26:02.670 --> 00:26:06.150
and you disagreed very
frequently on legal matters.

00:26:06.150 --> 00:26:10.560
And students, I want to make sure
you understand that Justice Scalia,

00:26:10.560 --> 00:26:14.580 position:56%
who was one of the other Justices
on the Court, sadly, died last year.

00:26:14.580 --> 00:26:17.460
But when he was alive,
the two of them ...

00:26:17.460 --> 00:26:18.760
oh my goodness.

00:26:18.760 --> 00:26:22.930
They disagreed strongly
on legal matters.

00:26:22.930 --> 00:26:27.660
Will you tell students, first,
about the back and forth that went

00:26:27.660 --> 00:26:29.790
on between you and Justice Scalia?

00:26:29.790 --> 00:26:31.210
That is, did you listen
to each other?

00:26:31.210 --> 00:26:34.940
Did you just show each other the
hand and say 'don't talk to me?'

00:26:34.940 --> 00:26:37.670
How was that?

00:26:39.660 --> 00:26:43.180 position:56%
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: When Justice
Scalia and I disagreed, and I wrote,

00:26:43.180 --> 00:26:47.040 position:56%
say, the opinion of the Court and he
dissented, or he wrote the opinion

00:26:47.040 --> 00:26:53.160
of the Court and I dissented, my
opinion was always much better

00:26:53.160 --> 00:26:57.090
in the end because he pointed
out all the weak spots,

00:26:57.090 --> 00:27:03.480
and then I was able to fix them
and make the opinion stronger.

00:27:03.480 --> 00:27:06.180
Justice Scalia was
very good at grammar.

00:27:06.180 --> 00:27:09.690
His mother was a grade
school grammar teacher

00:27:09.690 --> 00:27:12.440
and his father taught Latin.

00:27:12.440 --> 00:27:18.240
So if I made mistakes in grammar,
he would call me on the telephone;

00:27:18.240 --> 00:27:20.720
wouldn't tell the rest of my
colleagues, and he's say, "Ruth,

00:27:20.720 --> 00:27:30.920
you know, you really should use
plural here instead of singular."

00:27:30.920 --> 00:27:37.500
And I would sometimes tell him,
"Your dissent is so overheated,

00:27:37.500 --> 00:27:42.240
you're going to lose people that
you might otherwise persuade

00:27:42.240 --> 00:27:46.220
if you moderated the tone."

00:27:46.220 --> 00:27:51.230
He didn't always listen
when I said that.

00:27:51.230 --> 00:27:54.200 position:56%
But I loved him and I've missed him.

00:27:54.200 --> 00:28:00.990 position:56%
One reason is, he had a wonderful
sense of humor and he made me laugh.

00:28:00.990 --> 00:28:02.290
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: So the two

00:28:02.290 --> 00:28:06.040
of you disagreed strenuously,
but were great friends.

00:28:06.040 --> 00:28:07.340
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: Yes.

00:28:07.340 --> 00:28:13.940 position:56%
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: Since we're here in
a great library, and I know that you

00:28:13.940 --> 00:28:17.200
as a girl went to the library
in Brooklyn with your mother,

00:28:17.200 --> 00:28:21.380
I want to ask why was reading
important to you as a child,

00:28:21.380 --> 00:28:25.710
and why do you think it's important
for our students here, reading?

00:28:25.710 --> 00:28:27.950
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG:
Because it opened vistas to me

00:28:27.950 --> 00:28:34.990
about far away places and
people who were different.

00:28:34.990 --> 00:28:38.630
My mother would leave me
at the library and I'd pick

00:28:38.630 --> 00:28:41.370
out five books to take home.

00:28:41.370 --> 00:28:44.630
And we'd check them out and
bring them back the next week,

00:28:44.630 --> 00:28:47.930
and find more books.

00:28:47.930 --> 00:28:53.250
Something that I loved that
was not real, Greek mythology.

00:28:53.250 --> 00:28:56.260
You mentioned Athena,
the goddess of wisdom.

00:28:56.260 --> 00:29:00.310 position:56%
I love to read about the Greek gods.

00:29:00.310 --> 00:29:01.800 position:56%
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: I wonder, what is it

00:29:01.800 --> 00:29:04.700
about the Greek gods
and mythology ...

00:29:04.700 --> 00:29:06.480
Percy Jackson, you all; right?

00:29:06.480 --> 00:29:08.160
Weren't we talking
about that before?

00:29:08.160 --> 00:29:12.140
What is it about that
that attracted you so?

00:29:12.140 --> 00:29:13.580
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG:
Well, for one thing,

00:29:13.580 --> 00:29:17.440
there was more equality
among the Greek gods

00:29:17.440 --> 00:29:19.660
with Athena the goddess of wisdom.

00:29:19.660 --> 00:29:25.370
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: There was equality
among the gods and goddesses.

00:29:25.370 --> 00:29:26.670
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: Yes.

00:29:26.670 --> 00:29:27.970
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: And
I know that you have

00:29:27.970 --> 00:29:31.280
to read a great many
legal papers for work,

00:29:31.280 --> 00:29:35.390
but do you find time
to read for pleasure?

00:29:35.390 --> 00:29:37.680
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: Yes,
I wish I could do a lot more

00:29:37.680 --> 00:29:43.050 position:56%
but I always take home a lot of work

00:29:43.050 --> 00:29:45.820
from the Court; a lot
of reading to do.

00:29:45.820 --> 00:29:48.200
But the last thing I do
before I fall asleep,

00:29:48.200 --> 00:29:53.290
if I've done a good job, I did all
my homework, and I get into bed

00:29:53.290 --> 00:29:56.340
with a good book and
read a few pages,

00:29:56.340 --> 00:29:57.970
usually fall asleep before ...

00:29:57.970 --> 00:30:04.180
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: I think
that's a good habit.

00:30:04.180 --> 00:30:10.700
Much as we love to read, a
person cannot read all the time.

00:30:10.700 --> 00:30:14.230
Sometimes, one has to
get up and move around.

00:30:14.230 --> 00:30:17.670
And you, Justice Ginsburg,
are known to spend some time

00:30:17.670 --> 00:30:20.430
at the gym in the Supreme Court.

00:30:20.430 --> 00:30:24.440 position:56%
You're an exercise buff, and I think
the students would be interested

00:30:24.440 --> 00:30:26.990
in your exercise routine.

00:30:26.990 --> 00:30:31.070
Can you talk to them about it?

00:30:31.070 --> 00:30:33.020
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG:
Tonight, I will meet my ...

00:30:33.020 --> 00:30:36.110
we call him "personal trainer,"

00:30:36.110 --> 00:30:41.500
and we will spend an hour together
doing all kinds of things ...

00:30:41.500 --> 00:30:53.490 position:56%
lifting weights, doing pushups,
planks, using the elliptical glider.

00:30:55.560 --> 00:31:01.660
I started working with a
personal trainer in 1999,

00:31:01.660 --> 00:31:04.790
long before you were born.

00:31:04.790 --> 00:31:08.870
And you know, the reason I started
was because I had been very sick.

00:31:08.870 --> 00:31:16.060
I had a disease called
cancer, and when I was finally

00:31:16.060 --> 00:31:20.770
through all the treatments,
I was not in very good shape.

00:31:20.770 --> 00:31:22.840
I was very weak.

00:31:22.840 --> 00:31:26.220
So my husband said, "You'd better
get yourself a personal trainer."

00:31:26.220 --> 00:31:27.520
Which I did.

00:31:27.520 --> 00:31:30.210
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: And you've
been exercising seriously ever

00:31:30.210 --> 00:31:31.510
since then.

00:31:31.510 --> 00:31:32.810
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: Yes.

00:31:32.810 --> 00:31:34.110
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: That's a long time.

00:31:34.110 --> 00:31:35.410
Now, I think I have time

00:31:35.410 --> 00:31:39.610
for a couple more questions
before opening it up to you.

00:31:39.610 --> 00:31:45.810
I have two final ones, and that
is, what is the best advice

00:31:45.810 --> 00:31:51.950
that you can give us on how
to react when someone argues

00:31:51.950 --> 00:31:55.020
with you by saying mean things?

00:31:55.020 --> 00:32:02.330
That is, attacks you rather than
engaging or going after your ideas?

00:32:02.330 --> 00:32:08.750
What about when it gets personal
as arguments sometimes do?

00:32:08.750 --> 00:32:11.910
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: My
best advice is to tune out.

00:32:11.910 --> 00:32:14.080
Don't try to argue back.

00:32:14.080 --> 00:32:16.090
Don't try to be mean in return.

00:32:16.090 --> 00:32:24.680
That's not going to
get you anyplace.

00:32:24.680 --> 00:32:29.950 position:56%
Try to use the good reasons you have
to persuade people, and for people

