00:35:48.300 --> 00:36:00.680
&gt;&gt; AUDIENCE: Was it your dream to
become a Supreme Court Justice?

00:36:00.680 --> 00:36:02.290
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: Did I
dream to become a Supreme ...

00:36:02.290 --> 00:36:03.590
?

00:36:03.590 --> 00:36:04.890
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: That's the
question, was it your dream

00:36:04.890 --> 00:36:07.190
to become a Supreme Court Justice?

00:36:09.390 --> 00:36:14.250
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG: People of
my advanced age, women who went

00:36:14.250 --> 00:36:18.460
to law school when I did,
dreamed of getting a job

00:36:18.460 --> 00:36:21.340
in the law, any job in the law.

00:36:21.340 --> 00:36:27.540 position:56%
There were no women judges so it
would have been an impossible dream.

00:36:29.690 --> 00:36:31.780
In fact, the first woman appointed

00:36:31.780 --> 00:36:38.420
to a federal trial bench was
appointed by Truman in 1948,

00:36:38.420 --> 00:36:45.630
and there had only been one
woman on a U.S. Court of Appeals;

00:36:45.630 --> 00:36:51.320
she was appointed by Franklin
Delano Roosevelt in 1934.

00:36:51.320 --> 00:36:57.500
And when she retired,
there were none again.

00:36:57.500 --> 00:37:00.040
So it would have been ...

00:37:00.040 --> 00:37:06.140
it could be something that was
beyond the realm of possibility.

00:37:06.140 --> 00:37:08.660
In fact, I didn't dream
about becoming a judge

00:37:08.660 --> 00:37:12.320 position:56%
until Jimmy Carter became President.

00:37:12.320 --> 00:37:17.730
And the reason I started then
is, he looked around at people

00:37:17.730 --> 00:37:22.080
who were judges in the United
States and he said, "You know,

00:37:22.080 --> 00:37:26.290
they all look like me, and
that's not how the great United

00:37:26.290 --> 00:37:27.620
States looks."

00:37:27.620 --> 00:37:29.300
When he said "they
all look like me,"

00:37:29.300 --> 00:37:33.010
he meant they were white
and they were male.

00:37:33.010 --> 00:37:39.170 position:56%
So he was determined to appoint
members of minority groups and women

00:37:39.170 --> 00:37:42.200
in numbers to the federal bench.

00:37:42.200 --> 00:37:48.190
So he appointed about 25 women
to the federal trial Court,

00:37:48.190 --> 00:37:52.780
and 11 to Courts of Appeals,
and I was one of the lucky 11.

00:37:55.190 --> 00:37:59.300
&gt;&gt; AUDIENCE: Why did you want to
become a Supreme Court Justice?

00:37:59.300 --> 00:38:01.720
&gt;&gt; DEBBIE LEVY: Why did you want
to become a Supreme Court Justice?

00:38:01.720 --> 00:38:04.060
&gt;&gt; RUTH BADER GINSBURG:
Because I think it's the best

00:38:04.060 --> 00:38:10.300
and the hardest job a
law-trained person can have.

00:38:10.300 --> 00:38:15.450
We have no cases that are
easy because most of the cases

00:38:15.450 --> 00:38:19.170
that we hear are cases
where other courts ...

00:38:19.170 --> 00:38:22.730
I'd better get myself
another Constitution;

00:38:22.730 --> 00:38:26.130
this one's falling apart ...

00:38:29.450 --> 00:38:34.970
So, my job is to do
a lot of reading,

00:38:34.970 --> 00:38:39.280 position:56%
a lot of thinking, a lot of writing.

00:38:39.280 --> 00:38:44.310
It's hard, but it's very
satisfying when I finish an opinion

00:38:44.310 --> 00:38:47.790
and I can say, "Yes, that's good.

00:38:47.790 --> 00:38:55.100
I hope it will persuade
the people who read it."

